{
  "sections": {
    "gp_section_612947718851002939": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "6521b28ae595f03c2044d72996502349cdcb5872adc25af2685d9641b7fa86ec_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg4t8aUY-gP_text": "5 Reasons UK Tradespeople Are Ditching Heavy Boots For Good",
        "ggKzU_rfIvb_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Avatar.png",
        "ggNgBGXdu-H_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41010.png",
        "ggPaS9yLzGu_text": "Your Safety Boots Are the Problem. Not the Job.",
        "ggdiAk0eJc2_label": "<p>Explore the Comfort</p>",
        "ggmVoAEAWxY_text": "<p>Last Updated Mar 3.2025</p>",
        "ggvHlTg1lPb_text": "<p>By <strong>Jessica M.</strong></p>",
        "ggyV04MX_qM_text": "<p>You finish a shift and your feet are done. Back's stiff. Knees ache. You've written it off as part of the job. Most workers do.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>They try a different brand, spend more money, get the same result, and eventually stop looking for an answer.&nbsp;</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But the answer isn't a better brand. It's understanding what's actually causing the damage. Here's what's going on</p>",
        "section_preload": "true"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947718851002939"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719287210555": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "f1612ad56c61eace764da0421b01b8324a8ebe6327303646628efb260a9739f4_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg8cPHYNwVd_text": "<p>This is what most people in the industry don't talk about.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>S3 is a performance standard. It defines what a boot has to protect against: impact, penetration, water, slip resistance. It does not say what materials you have to use to get there.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>For decades, manufacturers used steel for everything. Steel toecap, steel midsole plate, steel reinforcements throughout. Steel is cheap. It works. And because the workers wearing the boots were never the ones specifying them, nobody in the supply chain ever had a reason to look for something better.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A small number of manufacturers figured out that Kevlar, the same material used in body armour, meets the S3 penetration standard at a fraction of the weight of a steel plate. The protection is identical. The certification is the same. It still passes site inspection. The shoe just weighs 460 grams.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>460 grams. That's lighter than most trainers.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The weight was never part of the safety requirement. It was just a side effect nobody bothered fixing.</p>",
        "gg9qEKQKEQ7_text": "The Safety Standard Has Nothing To Do With the Weight",
        "ggtwgd7yaBb_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41018.png"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719287210555"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719371096635": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "a818d1814f5e36b5d09731c0d9529986e9c9dad6d8d00e0c47c40472b02f54a9_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg5jp5xOybH_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41017.png",
        "ggSQMRMiuol_text": "Your Boots Are Working Against You All Day Long",
        "ggezJjNqnNl_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41017.png",
        "ggyTRmUd0ss_text": "<p>Ask any tradesperson what hurts most by the end of a shift and you hear the same things. Feet. Lower back. That heavy dragging feeling in your joints that doesn't go away over the weekend.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>That's not just a hard day on the tools. That's what happens when you strap over a kilogram of dead weight to each foot before you've even left the house.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Traditional safety boots weigh well over 1kg per shoe. You're walking 10,000 to 15,000 steps a day on concrete. On hard floor. On site ground. Every step, your legs are lifting that load. Your hips compensate. Your lower back absorbs what your legs can't manage.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><i><strong>\"My feet are killing me by lunchtime\"</strong></i> is not the job talking. It's the boots.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The work is hard enough without carrying extra weight your body was never supposed to deal with.</p>"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719371096635"
    },
    "gp_section_612947719538868960": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "93d16240841a5b57b666c9e2d4d6b0afdb9748fc1532211d93b10eeada7c25f1_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg5rfYIcy-A_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41020.png",
        "ggBfECCthge_text": "<p>There's a belief on site that weight means protection. That if a boot is light, something's been cut somewhere. That serious work needs serious kit.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It's understandable. For a long time it was true. When steel was the only material that hit S3 standards, weight was the price you paid for compliance.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But you wouldn't pick a power drill from 1995 because it feels more solid. You wouldn't choose heavier scaffolding because it looks more robust. You'd choose what does the job properly.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A 460 gram shoe with a Kevlar plate and a steel toecap passes the same S3 certification as a boot twice the weight. Same impact protection. Same anti-puncture standard. Same site inspection. It just doesn't punish your body while doing it.</p>",
        "ggk9KCanWGj_text": "Heavy Boots Are Not Safer. They Are Just Older."
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947719538868960"
    },
    "gp_section_612947720209957600": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "7e66c0a24cd522a2e59c1054ebd4821248d94c082bf86413286c3c6cc29e693c_1_1_1_0__1",
        "ggNSNHojJ3l_text": "Your Boots Are Destroying Your Feet Before the Concrete Even Gets a Chance",
        "ggbH4SmoZ3v_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41021.png",
        "gghLPyCk2qj_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41021.png",
        "gglhiZ70pao_text": "<p>Most workers blame the concrete. Hard floors. Long hours standing. And yes, all of that plays a part.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>But the boot itself is making it significantly worse.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Traditional safety boots are built around a rigid last and thick leather upper. That rigidity means the boot doesn't flex with your foot. It forces your foot to adapt to the shoe rather than the other way around. Over an eight hour shift, that constant resistance causes friction at the heel and toe box. That's where the blisters come from. That's why your ankles feel locked up by the afternoon.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The stiffness isn't a sign of quality. It's what happens when a boot is designed around a safety standard rather than around a human foot.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>A boot that weighs 460 grams and flexes like a trainer doesn't just reduce fatigue from the weight. It stops fighting your foot all day long. The blisters ease. The ankle stiffness goes. The feet that were done by lunchtime start making it to the end of the shift in one piece.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>The concrete isn't going anywhere. But what you put on your feet before you step onto it is entirely your choice.</p>"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947720209957600"
    },
    "gp_section_612947721199813179": {
      "settings": {
        "checksum": "74b9e647018facb9c9bd4c705528ca9dabeacafbea4c36983b0bf303207f51fb_1_1_1_0__1",
        "gg8QfDv3jhZ_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41019.png",
        "ggAITJL6-40_text": "<p>The difference between a traditional safety boot and a modern lightweight one is roughly 500 grams per foot.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Doesn't sound like much. Run it across a full shift.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>At 12,000 steps a day, 500 grams extra per foot means your legs and lower back are absorbing thousands of additional kilograms of load every single day. Five days a week. Every week you're on the tools.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Your body isn't struggling because you're getting older or because site work is hard. It's struggling because it has been doing unnecessary work from the moment you put your boots on in the morning.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>Workers who made the switch describe the same thing in the first few weeks. They're still tired after a shift but it feels different. The heavy dragging exhaustion that sits in your joints starts to ease. Back pain they'd written off as permanent begins to shift.</p><p>&nbsp;</p><p>It was never the age. It was always the weight.</p>",
        "ggTAX4bfxJt_text": "The Damage Adds Up Faster Than You Think",
        "ggaRtiqng48_srcSet_desktop_src": "https://cdn.shopify.com/s/files/1/0673/2562/4490/files/Rectangle_41019.png"
      },
      "type": "gp-section-612947721199813179"
    },
